## Description {#details}

This file defines the SmallPtrSet class.

See the doxygen comment for SmallPtrSetImplBase for more details on the algorithm used.

<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SmallPtrSetImplBase - This is the common code shared among all the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SmallPtrSet&lt;&gt;&#39;s, which is almost everything.  SmallPtrSet has two modes, one</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// for small and one for large sets.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Small sets use an array of pointers allocated in the SmallPtrSet object,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// which is treated as a simple array of pointers.  When a pointer is added to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the set, the array is scanned to see if the element already exists, if not</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the element is &#39;pushed back&#39; onto the array.  If we run out of space in the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// array, we grow into the &#39;large set&#39; case.  SmallSet should be used when the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// sets are often small.  In this case, no memory allocation is used, and only</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// light-weight and cache-efficient scanning is used.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Large sets use a classic exponentially-probed hash table.  Empty buckets are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// represented with an illegal pointer value (-1) to allow null pointers to be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// inserted.  Tombstones are represented with another illegal pointer value</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// (-2), to allow deletion.  The hash table is resized when the table is 3/4 or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// more.  When this happens, the table is doubled in size.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00514" /><CodeLine lineNumber="514"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SmallPtrSet - This class implements a set which is optimized for holding</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00515" /><CodeLine lineNumber="515"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SmallSize or less elements.  This internally rounds up SmallSize to the next</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00516" /><CodeLine lineNumber="516"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// power of two if it is not already a power of two.  See the comments above</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00520" /><CodeLine lineNumber="520"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// In small mode SmallPtrSet uses linear search for the elements, so it is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00521" /><CodeLine lineNumber="521"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// not a good idea to choose this value too high. You may consider using a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00522" /><CodeLine lineNumber="522"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// DenseSet&lt;&gt; instead if you expect many elements in the set.</span></CodeLine>
